
⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ Question 69/120 – Consecutive Login Days

🎤 Interview Question

You are given a user login DataFrame.

Write PySpark code to identify users who logged in for 3 or more consecutive days.


---

📊 Input Dataset

user_id	login_date

101	2024-01-01
101	2024-01-02
101	2024-01-03
101	2024-01-05
102	2024-02-10
102	2024-02-11
103	2024-03-01



---

✅ Expected Output

user_id

101



---

✅ Recommended Solution

from pyspark.sql.window import Window
from pyspark.sql.functions import (
    row_number,
    datediff,
    date_sub,
    col,
    count
)

window_spec = Window.partitionBy("user_id").orderBy("login_date")

result = (
    df.withColumn("rn", row_number().over(window_spec))
      .withColumn("grp", date_sub(col("login_date"), col("rn")))
      .groupBy("user_id", "grp")
      .agg(count("*").alias("days"))
      .filter(col("days") >= 3)
      .select("user_id")
)

result.show()


---

🎤 Most Asked Interview Questions

Q1. Why do we create a grouping key using date_sub() and row_number()?

Answer

It assigns the same group identifier to consecutive dates, making it easy to count consecutive-day streaks.


---

Q2. Is this question common?

Answer

Yes. It's frequently asked for user activity, attendance, and transaction streak analysis.


---

Q3. Real-world use cases?

Answer

User login streaks

Employee attendance

Daily purchases

App engagement metrics



